[4] USA: Louisiana (New Orleans) travel associated
Date: Fri 11 May 2018
Source: The Advocate [edited]
http://www.theadvocate.com/new_orleans/news/environment/article_21c6b8c6-554f-11e8-bfdd-47f961fabe9a.html


A New Orleans area resident has become the 2nd person in the state to contract the highly contagious measles virus, but health officials said [Fri 11 May 2018] the risk of a broader outbreak is low.

Doctors confirmed the case on [Thu 10 May 2018] and believe the resident likely contracted the disease while traveling abroad, according to Dr. Frank Welch of the state's Office of Public Health.

The case this week is the 2nd in Louisiana since the start of April [2018], Welch said. The 1st case was also from someone who had traveled abroad. No secondary infections were reported from that case, even though the person attended what Welch called a "public event."

Nationwide, several dozen people contract the disease every year. The most recent outbreak was centered on a California amusement park [2015].

"The outbreak likely started from a traveler who became infected overseas ... then visited the amusement park while infectious," according to the CDC's website. That outbreak, and one the previous year [2016], were related to a large 2014 outbreak of the disease in the Philippines.

Another 2014 outbreak in the United States occurred in a mostly unvaccinated Amish community in Ohio, according to the CDC.

[Byline: Faimon Roberts]

